Content:
This is my question: How to evaluate or prove this integral: \begin{equation}
\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cot^{-1} \left(a\sin x+\sqrt{a^2-1}\right) \mathrm{d}x\\
=\frac{1}{2}\left(\sin^{-1}\frac{1}{\sqrt a}\right)^2+\frac{1}{2}\left(\sinh^{-1}\frac{1}{\sqrt a}\right)^2
\end{equation} for $a \ge 1$ . $\textbf{My Attempt:}$ Let : $\displaystyle I =\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cot^{-1} \left(a\sin x+\sqrt{a^2-1}\right) \ \mathrm{d}x$ , and we have: \begin{equation}
I=\frac{\pi}{2}\cot^{-1}(\cosh^{-1}(a))+\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \frac{x\cos x}{a+a \sin ^{2} x+2 \sqrt{a^{2}-1}\sin x} d x .
\end{equation} I couldn't get any more efficient calculations. So I try Feynman's trick \begin{equation}
I'(a)=-\frac{1}{a}\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\left(\sin x+\frac{a}{\sqrt{a^2-1}}\right)\frac{1}{a+a \sin ^{2} x+2 \sqrt{a^{2}-1}\sin x} d x .
\end{equation} I still feel at a loss about this.Could anybody give me some hints? Thanks!

AcceptedAnswer:
Consider \begin{align}
I(p)&=\int_0^{\pi/2}\cot^{-1}(\sec p \cos x +\tan p)dx\\
I’(p)&=-\int_0^{\pi/2}\frac{1+\sin p\cos x}{1+2\sin p\cos x +\cos^2 x}dx\>\>\>\>\>(t= \tan\frac x2)\\
&= -\int_0^1 \frac{(1+\sin p)+ (1-\sin p) t^2}{(1+\sin p)+ (1-\sin p) t^4}\ dt\\
 &= -\frac{\sin\frac p2\ \sinh^{-1}\sqrt{\cos p}}{\sqrt{2\cos p}}  -\frac{\cos\frac p2\ \sin^{-1} \sqrt{\cos p}}{\sqrt{2\cos p}}\\
\end{align} With $I(\frac\pi2)=0$ \begin{align}
I(p)&=I(\frac\pi2)-\int_p^{\pi/2}I’(s)ds\\
&= \int_p^{\pi/2}\frac{\sin\frac s2\ \sinh^{-1}\sqrt{\cos s}}{\sqrt{2\cos s}}  +\frac{\cos\frac s2\ \sin^{-1}\sqrt{\cos s}}{\sqrt{2\cos s}}ds\\
&=\bigg[-\frac12\text{arcsinh}^2 \sqrt{\cos s}
 -\frac12\text{arcsin}^2 \sqrt{\cos s}\bigg]_p^{\pi/2}\\
 &= \frac12\text{arcsinh}^2\sqrt{\cos p}
 +\frac12\text{arcsin}^2 \sqrt{\cos p}
\end{align} Replace $\cos p=\frac1a$ to obtain $$\int_0^{\pi/2}\cot^{-1}\left(a\sin x +\sqrt{a^2-1}\right)dx
= \frac12\text{arcsinh}^2\frac1{\sqrt a}
 +\frac12\text{arcsin}^2 \frac1{\sqrt a}
$$
